instructions:
## Set up Sanity CMS in Next.js

Sanity is a headless CMS with real-time collaboration, a customizable embedded Studio, and GROQ — a powerful query language for structured content.

### 1. Create a Sanity project
- Run: `npx sanity@latest init` and follow the prompts. This creates a project on sanity.io and generates a `sanity.config.ts`.
- Alternatively, go to sanity.io/manage, create a project manually, and note the **Project ID** and **Dataset** (default: `production`).

### 2. Install packages
- Run: `npm install next-sanity sanity @sanity/image-url`
- `next-sanity` provides the Sanity client and Studio wrapper for Next.js.
- `@sanity/image-url` builds CDN-optimized image URLs.

### 3. Configure environment variables
- Add to `.env.local`:
  ```
  NEXT_PUBLIC_SANITY_PROJECT_ID=your-project-id
  NEXT_PUBLIC_SANITY_DATASET=production
  NEXT_PUBLIC_SANITY_API_VERSION=2024-01-01
  ```
- For private datasets, also add: `SANITY_API_READ_TOKEN=your-read-token` (server-side only, no `NEXT_PUBLIC_` prefix).

### 4. Create the Sanity client
- Create `src/sanity/client.ts`:
  ```typescript
  import { createClient } from 'next-sanity';

  export const client = createClient({
    projectId: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SANITY_PROJECT_ID!,
    dataset: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SANITY_DATASET!,
    apiVersion: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SANITY_API_VERSION!,
    useCdn: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production',
  });
  ```
- `useCdn: true` serves cached responses from Sanity's CDN — faster for production, not suitable for drafts.

### 5. Define content schemas
- Create `src/sanity/schemaTypes/post.ts`:
  ```typescript
  import { defineField, defineType } from 'sanity';

  export const postType = defineType({
    name: 'post',
    title: 'Post',
    type: 'document',
    fields: [
      defineField({ name: 'title', title: 'Title', type: 'string' }),
      defineField({
        name: 'slug',
        title: 'Slug',
        type: 'slug',
        options: { source: 'title' },
      }),
      defineField({
        name: 'body',
        title: 'Body',
        type: 'array',
        of: [{ type: 'block' }],
      }),
      defineField({
        name: 'mainImage',
        title: 'Main Image',
        type: 'image',
        options: { hotspot: true },
      }),
      defineField({ name: 'publishedAt', title: 'Published At', type: 'datetime' }),
    ],
  });
  ```
- Create `src/sanity/schemaTypes/index.ts`:
  ```typescript
  import { postType } from './post';
  export const schemaTypes = [postType];
  ```

### 6. Create the Studio config
- Create (or update) `sanity.config.ts` in the project root:
  ```typescript
  import { defineConfig } from 'sanity';
  import { structureTool } from 'sanity/structure';
  import { schemaTypes } from './src/sanity/schemaTypes';

  export default defineConfig({
    name: 'default',
    title: 'My Project',
    projectId: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SANITY_PROJECT_ID!,
    dataset: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SANITY_DATASET!,
    plugins: [structureTool()],
    schema: { types: schemaTypes },
  });
  ```

### 7. Embed Studio in Next.js
- Create `src/app/studio/[[...tool]]/page.tsx`:
  ```typescript
  'use client';
  import { NextStudio } from 'next-sanity/studio';
  import config from '../../../../sanity.config';

  export const dynamic = 'force-dynamic';

  export default function StudioPage() {
    return <NextStudio config={config} />;
  }
  ```
- Visit `/studio` in the browser to access the full Sanity Studio editor.
- Protect this route behind authentication in production (Clerk, Auth.js, etc.).

### 8. Write GROQ queries
- Create `src/sanity/queries.ts`:
  ```typescript
  import { groq } from 'next-sanity';

  export const postsQuery = groq`*[_type == "post"] | order(publishedAt desc) {
    _id,
    title,
    slug,
    publishedAt,
    mainImage
  }`;

  export const postBySlugQuery = groq`*[_type == "post" && slug.current == $slug][0] {
    _id,
    title,
    body,
    mainImage,
    publishedAt
  }`;
  ```
- GROQ is Sanity's query language. `*[_type == "post"]` selects all documents of type `post`.

### 9. Fetch data in Server Components
  ```typescript
  import { client } from '@/sanity/client';
  import { postsQuery, postBySlugQuery } from '@/sanity/queries';

  export default async function PostsPage() {
    const posts = await client.fetch(postsQuery);
    return (
      <ul>
        {posts.map((post: { _id: string; title: string }) => (
          <li key={post._id}>{post.title}</li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    );
  }

  // For dynamic routes:
  export default async function PostPage({ params }: { params: { slug: string } }) {
    const post = await client.fetch(postBySlugQuery, { slug: params.slug });
    return <article>{post.title}</article>;
  }
  ```

### 10. Handle images
- Create `src/sanity/image.ts`:
  ```typescript
  import imageUrlBuilder from '@sanity/image-url';
  import type { SanityImageSource } from '@sanity/image-url/lib/types/types';
  import { client } from './client';

  const builder = imageUrlBuilder(client);

  export function urlFor(source: SanityImageSource) {
    return builder.image(source);
  }
  ```
- Use in a component:
  ```typescript
  import Image from 'next/image';
  import { urlFor } from '@/sanity/image';

  const imageUrl = urlFor(post.mainImage).width(800).height(400).url();
  return <Image src={imageUrl} alt={post.title} width={800} height={400} />;
  ```

### 11. Configure CORS
- Go to sanity.io/manage → your project → API → CORS Origins.
- Add `http://localhost:3000` for local development.
- Add your production URL before deploying (e.g., `https://myapp.vercel.app`).
- Without CORS configuration, browser-side requests and the Studio will be blocked.

### 12. Verify the setup
- Start the dev server: `npm run dev`.
- Visit `/studio` — the Sanity Studio should load with your schema types.
- Create a test post in the Studio and publish it.
- Visit the page that calls `client.fetch(postsQuery)` — the published post should appear.

### Common errors & fixes
- **Studio shows blank page or CORS error in console** — Add your localhost URL to CORS Origins in sanity.io/manage.
- **'Cannot find module sanity'** — Run `npm install sanity next-sanity`.
- **`projectId is required`** — Check that `NEXT_PUBLIC_SANITY_PROJECT_ID` is set in `.env.local` and the dev server was restarted.
- **`client.fetch()` returns an empty array** — Your dataset may be empty, or the GROQ filter `_type == "post"` does not match. Check the `name` field in your schema definition.
- **Image URL returns null** — Pass the full `mainImage` object (not just the asset reference) to `urlFor()`. The field must be type `image` with `hotspot: true` in the schema.
- **Schema types do not appear in Studio** — Verify `schemaTypes` is exported from `src/sanity/schemaTypes/index.ts` and imported in `sanity.config.ts`.
- **`dynamic = 'force-dynamic'` causes error** — The Studio page must be a Client Component (`'use client'`). Ensure both the directive and `export const dynamic = 'force-dynamic'` are present.
- **Stale content after editing** — In development, set `useCdn: false`. In production, trigger revalidation via `revalidatePath` or a Sanity webhook calling `revalidateTag`.

### What NOT to do
- Do NOT expose `SANITY_API_READ_TOKEN` to the browser — prefix with `NEXT_PUBLIC_` only for values safe to be public. The read token is server-side only.
- Do NOT leave `/studio` unprotected in production — anyone with the URL can edit content. Add an auth check (Clerk, Auth.js) or move it to a separate deployment.
- Do NOT use `useCdn: true` when fetching draft content — CDN responses are cached and will not show unpublished changes.
- Do NOT fetch Sanity data in Client Components — use Server Components or `generateStaticParams` for SEO and performance.
- Do NOT skip CORS configuration — browser queries and the Studio will silently fail without it.
- Do NOT use raw Sanity image asset URLs directly — always use `@sanity/image-url` for CDN delivery and image transformations.
- Do NOT hardcode projectId in `sanity.config.ts` — use `process.env` so it works across environments.
